.TH PDSYNC 1 "December 2025" "pdsync 1.9" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
pdsync \- synchronize two local directories in parallel
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pdsync
[options] <fromdir> <todir>
.SH DESCRIPTION
pdsync is a tool for fast, parallel synchronization of two local directories. It supports a variety of options for controlling what is copied, how metadata is handled, and performance tuning.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B -n, --dry-run
Perform a trial run with no changes made.
.TP
.B -i, --itemize
Output a shell script that replicates the changes pdsync would make to the target directory. 
Useful with --dry-run to preview changes and optionally apply them later. 
If repeated, includes comments about files not updated.
.TP
.B -P, --progress
Show progress information on the terminal. 
-PP shows also changes made to target directory. 
-PPP shows statistics of seen files and directories. 
-PPPP shows internal information useful mostly for debugging.
.TP
.B -V, --version
Show version information and exit.
.TP
.B -h, --help
Show help message and exit.
.TP
.B -x, --one-file-system
Do not cross filesystem boundaries.
.TP
.B -q, --quiet
Suppress non-error messages. Repeat for more quietness.
.TP
.B -d, --delete
Delete files in the destination that are not in the source.
.TP
.B -a, --archive
Archive mode; equivalent to -rlptgoD (recursive, links, perms, times, group, owner, devices).
.TP
.B -l, --links
Copy symlinks as symlinks.
.TP
.B -p, --perms
Preserve permissions.
.TP
.B -o, --owner
Preserve owner (root only).
.TP
.B -g, --group
Preserve group.
.TP
.B -D, --devices
Preserve device files (not implemented).
.TP
.B -t, --times
Preserve modification times.
.TP
.B -r, --recursive
Recurse into directories.
.TP
.B -U, --update
Check all files for differences regardless of timestamps and update them if needed. 
.TP
.B -S, --sparse
Handle sparse files efficiently.
.TP
.B -H, --hard-links
Preserve hard links.
.TP
.B -X, --exclude-regex <regex>
Exclude files matching the given regular expression.
.TP
.B --copy-job-size <MB>
Set the copy job size in megabytes (default: 1, max: 128).
.TP
.B --io_uring
Use io_uring for file operations (experimental).
.TP
.B --atimes
Preserve access times.
.TP
.B --privacy
Hide file paths in error messages.
.TP
.B --delete-only
Only delete files in the destination, do not copy.
.TP
.B --threads <N>
Set the number of worker threads (1â€“256). 
Every thread needs at least 4 file descriptors so you might consider 
using ulimit -n to make more file descriptors available. 
.TP
.B --sync-tag <tag>
Set a synchronization tag.
.TP
.B --sync-tag-name <name>
Set the name for the synchronization tag.
.TP
.B --debug
Enable debug output.
.TP
.B --check
Enable extra file checks.
.TP
.B --stats
Print statistics after completion.
.TP
.B --reflink
.TP
.B --reflink
Use copy-on-write (reflink). This requires support from the filesystem and source and target must be on the same filesystem.
.SH EXAMPLES
Synchronize two directories:
.nf
pdsync -a /src/dir /dst/dir
.fi

Dry run, showing what would be changed:
.nf
pdsync -ni /src/dir /dst/dir
.fi
